,\n  residualAtomicState Γ A = some (Δ, s) →\n  Relation.ReflTransGen AtomicResidualGraphStep (Δ, s) q →\n  q.2 = s ∧ ∀ B ∈ q.1, ∃ C ∈ Γ ++ [A], Subformula B C', 'prelude_code': 'lemma subformula_trans {A B C : Tp} : Subformula A B → Subformula B C → Subformula A C := by\n  intro hAB hBC\n  induction hBC with\n  | refl => exact hAB\n  | ldiv_left h ih => exact Subformula.ldiv_left ih\n  | ldiv_right h ih => exact Subformula.ldiv_right ih\n  | rdiv_left h ih => exact Subformula.rdiv_left ih\n  | rdiv_right h ih => exact Subformula.rdiv_right ih', 'prover_statement_result': 'ok', 'prover_attempts_used': 1, 'priority_refresh_ran': True, 'priority_refresh_error': '', 'expand_candidates': [{'statement': 'For any finite source list Σ and states p q, if every formula in p.1 is a subformula of some formula in Σ and AtomicResidualGraphStep p q, then q.2 = p.2 and every formula in q.1 is a subformula of some formula in Σ.', 'rationale': 'The solved theorem was proved by propagating a one-step closure property through reachability. Isolating that closure as its own theorem turns the current argument into a reusable invariant principle, which is the right abstraction for later finiteness and internal-automaton results rather than redoing reachability inductions from a specific residual root.'}, {'statement': 'There exist Γ A Δ s and q such that residualAtomicState Γ A = some (Δ, s), q.2 = s, and every formula in q.1 is a subformula of some formula in Γ ++ [A], but q is not reachable from (Δ, s).', 'rationale': 'The new theorem gives a necessary condition for reachability. Determining whether that condition is strictly weaker than actual reachability would clarify the boundary of the residual-control story: if strict, then subformula-bounded slices are only over-approximations and later automata constructions will need a sharper reachability criterion, not just the subformula invariant.'}], 'stored_expand_rows': [{'id': 'op_000068', 'stmt': 'For any finite source list Σ and stat